ROOTLESS, systemd --user. Bake in these hard-won requirements exactly — do NOT
"simplify" them away (each one is a documented failure we already hit):

  - Runs rootless as the `solace` service user via a systemd --user unit;
    linger enabled; container started ONLY by `systemctl --user`, never by
    invoking podman-compose directly.
  - compose service sets:  user: "1000:1000"
        (image default UID is 1000001, which overflows the rootless subuid
        range and fails with `setresuid to 1000001: Invalid argument`)
  - ulimits: nofile soft 2448 / hard 1048576
        (Solace POST aborts with "POST Violation [022] ... nofile 1048576 is
        required" if the hard limit is lower)
  - NO memlock key in the compose ulimits — it breaks `podman exec`
    (setrlimit not permitted in the exec shell). memlock comes from the user
    manager instead (see prereq below).
  - shm_size: 1g
  - storage-group bind-mounted to /var/lib/solace with :Z relabel, owned by the
    mapped container UID (use `podman unshare chown`).

HOST PREREQUISITE TASKS (run as root / via the hardening-adjacent path):
  - Create /etc/systemd/system/user@.service.d/solace-limits.conf with:
        [Service]
        LimitNOFILE=1048576
        LimitMEMLOCK=infinity
        LimitCORE=infinity
    then daemon-reload and restart user@<solace_uid>.service. Rootless cannot
    exceed the user-manager ceiling, so this MUST be set before the broker
    starts. Verify with `systemctl show user@<uid>.service -p LimitNOFILE`.
  - Enable linger for the solace user (loginctl enable-linger).
  - IF podman graphroot/runroot are relocated off the default (read the user's
    ~/.config/containers/storage.conf): apply SELinux fcontext equivalence to
    /var/lib/containers and run restorecon on those paths. Without this the
    container's libraries fail to load ("cannot change memory protections").
    Make this conditional — skip cleanly if storage is at the default path.

